# read img and convert color
img = cv2.imread('images.jpg')
img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

# build a transformation matrix for 25% both in +x and +y direction
matrix = [[1.25, 0, 0], #x 
          [0, 1.25, 0]] #y
t = np.float32(matrix)
h, w = img.shape[:2]

# transform
img_trans = cv2.warpAffine(img, t, (w, h))

# plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(12,8))
ax.axis('off')  

# plt.figure(1)
plt.subplot(121)
plt.imshow(img)

plt.subplot(122)
plt.imshow(img_trans)

In [4]:
h, w = img_trans.shape[:2]
# (w/2, h/2) -> center of the image

# rotation around z-axis by +90 degrees
T = cv2.getRotationMatrix2D((w/2, h/2), 90, 1)
img_rotated_postive90 = cv2.warpAffine(img_trans, T, (w, h))
# rotation around z-axis by -90 degrees
T = cv2.getRotationMatrix2D((w/2, h/2), -90, 1)
img_rotated_negative90 = cv2.warpAffine(img_rotated_postive90, T, (w, h))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(12,8))
ax.axis('off') 

plt.subplot(131)
plt.imshow(img_trans)

plt.subplot(132)
plt.imshow(img_rotated_postive90)

plt.subplot(133)
plt.imshow(img_rotated_negative90)

  1. From the center of the image, in all directions, increase the RGB values of the pixels in a manner that, each pixel from the center, the percentage drops by 1%. i.e. the center pixel's RGB will increase by 50%, and the next pixels in x and y directions will be 49%. This goes on and on until the increase becomes 0 %.
